00:03:02.230 --> 00:03:04.146
Kenya Vehicle Manufacturers.

00:03:06.900 --> 00:03:07.930
After I worked in Kenya
for a little

00:03:07.930 --> 00:03:09.270
while, I worked in Iraq.

00:03:09.270 --> 00:03:12.780
And I was like the super peon
at the State Department.

00:03:12.780 --> 00:03:15.500
And what my job was was
basically to put out fires,

00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:19.180
literally, between like a lot
of the contractors and the

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:20.440
policymakers.

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:22.340
And for those of you who
followed reconstruction in

00:03:22.340 --> 00:03:23.990
Iraq, you may have noticed
that what a lot of the

00:03:23.990 --> 00:03:26.780
policymakers were saying from a
technical standpoint didn't

00:03:26.780 --> 00:03:28.100
really make sense.

00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:29.840
And my portfolio was
electricity.

00:03:29.840 --> 00:03:31.540
And so here you see I'm actually
standing in front of

00:03:31.540 --> 00:03:36.915
a power plant in Dora, which
is just south of Baghdad.

00:03:36.915 --> 00:03:40.770
The big lesson learned there
is the US government only

00:03:40.770 --> 00:03:43.420
really thought about trying
to get the power up.

00:03:43.420 --> 00:03:46.710
Remember how I said that the
policymakers were focused on

00:03:46.710 --> 00:03:47.940
these things that didn't
make sense?

00:03:47.940 --> 00:03:50.740
Well, one of them was how many
megawatts can we produce?

00:03:50.740 --> 00:03:52.770
I think any of us who remember
high school physics know it's

00:03:52.770 --> 00:03:53.745
actually not about megawatts.

00:03:53.745 --> 00:03:56.370
It's about megawatt hours.

00:03:56.370 --> 00:03:59.220
And what it really is about is
if an Iraqi, at the end of the

00:03:59.220 --> 00:04:00.880
day, can flip a switch
on the wall, and

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:01.990
their power comes on.

00:04:01.990 --> 00:04:02.390
Right?

00:04:02.390 --> 00:04:04.540
The numbers are kind
of meaningless.

00:04:04.540 --> 00:04:07.870
But the US government didn't
think about, for example,

00:04:07.870 --> 00:04:09.160
where the fuel was going
to come from to

00:04:09.160 --> 00:04:10.020
run these power plants.

00:04:10.020 --> 00:04:12.040
They were very busy rebuilding
these power plants.

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:14.940
They didn't think about where
the power was going to go from

00:04:14.940 --> 00:04:17.610
the power plants in the
transmission lines, which I

00:04:17.610 --> 00:04:18.860
have another picture for you.

00:04:21.519 --> 00:04:24.720
This is a transmission line
between Baghdad and Dora.

00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:26.110
And it's very easy to
bring one down.

00:04:26.110 --> 00:04:28.070
This is one of the super
highways of power.

00:04:28.070 --> 00:04:29.920
There are only four going
in and out of Baghdad.

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:32.010
And you can strap an explosive
to the leg--

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:33.330
it's sad that I know this--
and you can bring

00:04:33.330 --> 00:04:34.490
it down very quickly.

00:04:34.490 --> 00:04:36.490
And this would happen during
election season.

00:04:36.490 --> 00:04:40.255
So kind of the lesson learned
for me at least was you can't

00:04:40.255 --> 00:04:41.760
just think about the thing,
the power plant.

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:43.280
You can't just think
about the tower.

00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:43.790
You have to think about
how the whole

00:04:43.790 --> 00:04:46.410
system works together.

00:04:46.410 --> 00:04:49.300
So that leads a little
bit into D-Rev, the

00:04:49.300 --> 00:04:50.860
organization I lead now.

00:04:50.860 --> 00:04:53.800
And D-Rev is short for
Design Revolution.

00:04:53.800 --> 00:04:55.640
And we are a nonprofit.

00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:57.790
And our mission is to
empower poor people.

00:04:57.790 --> 00:04:59.400
And when we talk about poor
people, what we really mean is

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:02.300
people living on less than $4
a day, but really about them

00:05:02.300 --> 00:05:03.430
empowering themselves.

00:05:03.430 --> 00:05:06.670
So getting away from the more
traditional foreign aid model,

00:05:06.670 --> 00:05:11.900
which is giving, and high cost,
and not necessarily

00:05:11.900 --> 00:05:14.780
higher return in terms of social
impact, but really

00:05:14.780 --> 00:05:17.270
looking to where do people
want to empower their own

00:05:17.270 --> 00:05:19.700
lives and supporting that.

00:05:19.700 --> 00:05:21.520
We focus on two areas.

00:05:21.520 --> 00:05:23.760
One of them is improving health
and improving income.

00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:25.520
And they're not opposite ends.

00:05:25.520 --> 00:05:27.170
Some of the products we work
on, like the knee, are

00:05:27.170 --> 00:05:28.220
actually both.

00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:30.430
If you can improve someone's
mobility, you're actually

00:05:30.430 --> 00:05:31.680
improving their income.

00:05:34.450 --> 00:05:37.920
We also focus on products
that scale.

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:42.400
So one of our founders, Paul
Polak, talks about products

00:05:42.400 --> 00:05:43.700
that at least reach a million.

00:05:43.700 --> 00:05:44.740
And sometimes he says
10 million.

00:05:44.740 --> 00:05:46.900
It really depends on his mood.

00:05:46.900 --> 00:05:49.280
But what I say is it's about
a lot of people.

00:05:49.280 --> 00:05:51.020
We're working on problems that
aren't necessarily at the

00:05:51.020 --> 00:05:51.740
village level.

00:05:51.740 --> 00:05:53.600
We're working on problems
that ideally are

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:56.770
at the global level.

00:05:56.770 --> 00:05:58.240
Three things to know about us.

00:05:58.240 --> 00:06:01.150
One is that we design products
that are world class.

00:06:01.150 --> 00:06:04.060
And if you know a little bit
about technology in the

00:06:04.060 --> 00:06:05.670
so-called developing world,
you know that there's this

00:06:05.670 --> 00:06:08.100
history of appropriate
technology, which is kind of

00:06:08.100 --> 00:06:13.170
like these rudimentary, low
cost, local materials products

00:06:13.170 --> 00:06:15.120
that were supposed
to help people.

00:06:15.120 --> 00:06:17.240
What we're saying is no, we're
designing world class

00:06:17.240 --> 00:06:19.750
products, products that if
you're a parent, you would use

00:06:19.750 --> 00:06:20.740
here with your children.

00:06:20.740 --> 00:06:22.990
We don't believe that just
because you're poor, you

00:06:22.990 --> 00:06:25.120
deserve products that are
any less quality.

00:06:25.120 --> 00:06:28.110
So when we say world class, we
mean products that perform on

00:06:28.110 --> 00:06:31.060
par or better than the best
products on the market.

00:06:31.060 --> 00:06:35.160
And this picture is actually
from east Delhi.

00:06:35.160 --> 00:06:38.230
The picture's me getting some
user feedback on one of our

00:06:38.230 --> 00:06:42.300
prototypes with some
doctors there.

00:06:42.300 --> 00:06:43.895
The second thing to know
about us is that

00:06:43.895 --> 00:06:44.800
we're market driven.

00:06:44.800 --> 00:06:49.360
And what that means is that we
leverage the private sector to

00:06:49.360 --> 00:06:52.750
manufacture, distribute,
and sell our products.

00:06:52.750 --> 00:06:55.510
And so, again, kind of in
contrast to the traditional

00:06:55.510 --> 00:06:59.080
foreign aid where things are
donated or someone has to buy

00:06:59.080 --> 00:07:01.760
stuff and donate it, if you
think about vaccines, for

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:03.730
example, that's never going
to be market driven.

00:07:03.730 --> 00:07:05.910
It doesn't mean that it's not
important, but it's not going

00:07:05.910 --> 00:07:07.570
to be economically
sustainable.

00:07:07.570 --> 00:07:09.460
We feel very strongly that
the products we work

00:07:09.460 --> 00:07:11.610
on are market driven.

00:07:11.610 --> 00:07:13.680
And the reason is that it
holds us accountable.

00:07:13.680 --> 00:07:15.720
If you don't design a good
product, people aren't

00:07:15.720 --> 00:07:17.250
going to buy it.

00:07:17.250 --> 00:07:19.670
But if you don't design a good
product and you donate it, you

00:07:19.670 --> 00:07:20.720
kind of don't care.

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:22.820
But what we really care about
is social impact.

00:07:22.820 --> 00:07:24.130
And we want people to buy it.

00:07:24.130 --> 00:07:26.810
And that way, it's economically
sustainable.

00:07:26.810 --> 00:07:28.580
The key thing though, of course,
is if you're going to

00:07:28.580 --> 00:07:30.920
design something that's market
driven, it does have to be

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:33.410
affordable.

00:07:33.410 --> 00:07:35.720
Next thing-- and this
is a picture of Vin.

00:07:35.720 --> 00:07:37.050
Let me just go back
for sec, too.

00:07:37.050 --> 00:07:39.400
One of the reasons I like
these pictures is on the

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:41.750
left-hand side, this is, I
think, how we often think of

00:07:41.750 --> 00:07:43.510
markets in the developing
world.

00:07:43.510 --> 00:07:44.560
But this is also a market.

00:07:44.560 --> 00:07:48.040
This is a medical device fair
in Dehli, our colleague,

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:49.290
[INAUDIBLE], here on the side.

00:07:51.900 --> 00:07:53.880
The third thing about us is
that we're user-obsessed.

00:07:53.880 --> 00:07:55.870
I know we all talk about
user-centric design.

00:07:55.870 --> 00:07:57.630
We try and take it
a step further.

00:07:57.630 --> 00:07:59.670
It's not just about the users,
or the stakeholders, and

00:07:59.670 --> 00:08:01.350
everyone in that
customer chain.

00:08:01.350 --> 00:08:02.960
It's about what's the context?

00:08:02.960 --> 00:08:04.200
How much power is there?

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:05.450
Are there voltage surges?

00:08:05.450 --> 00:08:06.570
What's the temperature?

00:08:06.570 --> 00:08:07.620
What does the market
look like?

00:08:07.620 --> 00:08:09.110
What's the landscape
of other products?

00:08:09.110 --> 00:08:11.020
How are people meeting
the need now?

00:08:11.020 --> 00:08:13.590
And if they're not meeting
the need, why not?

00:08:13.590 --> 00:08:16.390
So the picture here of my
colleague, Vin, in Ecuador

00:08:16.390 --> 00:08:20.640
talking to one of our amputees
who's wearing our version two

00:08:20.640 --> 00:08:22.870
of the knee.

00:08:22.870 --> 00:08:24.460
So what do we do?

00:08:24.460 --> 00:08:26.210
So D-Rev is based in
San Francisco.

00:08:26.210 --> 00:08:28.100
We like to say that we have
one foot here in Silicon

00:08:28.100 --> 00:08:31.850
Valley and one foot in
the places we work.

00:08:31.850 --> 00:08:33.360
If you think about the
design process--

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:35.900
I know for those of you who
develop products, this is a

00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:37.090
total oversimplification.

00:08:37.090 --> 00:08:40.390
And we agree, but identify
is the problem.

00:08:40.390 --> 00:08:42.039
Identifying what the problem
is, understanding the

00:08:42.039 --> 00:08:44.390
landscape, what's the market
look like, what do the supply

00:08:44.390 --> 00:08:46.950
channels look like, how are
things being met now, what are

00:08:46.950 --> 00:08:48.080
the challenges?

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:49.930
Design is what we kind of
think about design.

00:08:49.930 --> 00:08:54.320
Conceptual design, iterating,
prototyping, moving down the

00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:56.970
way to design for
manufacturability and getting

00:08:56.970 --> 00:08:58.930
ready for a market-ready
product.

00:08:58.930 --> 00:09:01.370
And then delivery for things
that we work on, which is

00:09:01.370 --> 00:09:04.380
hardware, is the manufacturing,
the

00:09:04.380 --> 00:09:07.600
distribution, getting it
from the manufacturing

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:09.360
door to the end user.

00:09:09.360 --> 00:09:10.530
So marketing could
be in there.

00:09:10.530 --> 00:09:13.980
If it's medical devices, what
else might be in there?

00:09:13.980 --> 00:09:15.110
I am going to pepper you
guys with questions

00:09:15.110 --> 00:09:16.830
every once in a while.

00:09:16.830 --> 00:09:20.730
Does anyone know with
medical devices?

00:09:20.730 --> 00:09:23.200
What else do you need to worry
about besides just like-- if I

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:24.890
want to put a medical device
out there, can I

00:09:24.890 --> 00:09:25.835
just go sell it?

00:09:25.835 --> 00:09:26.120
AUDIENCE: No.

00:09:26.120 --> 00:09:27.500
You need certification.

00:09:27.500 --> 00:09:28.700
KRISTA DONALDSON: Yes.

00:09:28.700 --> 00:09:31.230
In most places, you do, turns
out not all of them.

00:09:31.230 --> 00:09:32.200
But this is something
we worry about.

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:33.700
And, of course, if we're going
to say we're going to develop

00:09:33.700 --> 00:09:36.310
a world class product, we want
to have external validation.

00:09:36.310 --> 00:09:39.070
It's not good enough,
particularly as a

00:09:39.070 --> 00:09:40.985
Western-based organization, to
come in and be like, we've

00:09:40.985 --> 00:09:41.890
designed this great product.

00:09:41.890 --> 00:09:44.010
How many times have people
heard that before, right?

00:09:44.010 --> 00:09:46.810
So we look for external
validation like regulatory

00:09:46.810 --> 00:09:50.090
approval or American Academy
of Pediatrics standards.

00:09:50.090 --> 00:09:52.030
So that would go in here, too.

00:09:52.030 --> 00:09:54.330
And then scaling is I had
mentioned how we're really

00:09:54.330 --> 00:09:56.740
looking for problems that
are at a large scale.

00:09:56.740 --> 00:09:58.510
So just because something
works in India doesn't

00:09:58.510 --> 00:10:01.510
necessarily mean it's going to
work in sub-Saharan Africa, or

00:10:01.510 --> 00:10:04.000
Kenya, or East Africa, or even
smaller markets-- and trying

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:06.880
to understand that, and what's
our strategy, moving into

00:10:06.880 --> 00:10:09.640
where there's an existing
real need.

00:10:09.640 --> 00:10:11.550
And then, because we're a
nonprofit, we want to measure

00:10:11.550 --> 00:10:12.210
the impact.

00:10:12.210 --> 00:10:14.050
And I'm very passionate about
this measuring, because I feel

00:10:14.050 --> 00:10:15.780
like you don't really understand
if you're reaching

00:10:15.780 --> 00:10:19.080
your goals if you don't
measure it, right?

00:10:19.080 --> 00:10:23.280
So I mentioned we're
a nonprofit.

00:10:23.280 --> 00:10:25.170
We say we like to act
like a for profit.

00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:26.950
And this has been really
interesting for me as D-Rev

00:10:26.950 --> 00:10:29.550
has been growing a little bit
because people kind of stumble

00:10:29.550 --> 00:10:30.330
on the nonprofit.

00:10:30.330 --> 00:10:32.070
And they think about it like,
oh, you're the charity model.

00:10:32.070 --> 00:10:34.700
But no, because we take this
market driven approach, we're

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:36.560
actually a lot like
a for profit.

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:38.520
And it was kind of cool when
one of our first products

00:10:38.520 --> 00:10:41.130
launched, people who were buying
it didn't even know

00:10:41.130 --> 00:10:43.790
that a nonprofit was behind
the product, which to us,

00:10:43.790 --> 00:10:44.570
that's great.

00:10:44.570 --> 00:10:46.695
Because we want them to be
buying the product based on

00:10:46.695 --> 00:10:51.250
its quality and the value that
it's offering people.

00:10:51.250 --> 00:10:54.520
So to give you an idea of how
our funding model works for

00:10:54.520 --> 00:10:59.030
something like this, we raise
grants for R&amp;D type money or

00:10:59.030 --> 00:11:01.300
for R&amp;D type work
in our design.

00:11:01.300 --> 00:11:04.360
And then, as I mentioned, we
leverage the private sector.

00:11:04.360 --> 00:11:06.400
So for example, we will license
the design to a

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:08.640
partner who will then
manufacture, sell it, and

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:09.800
distribute it.

00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:12.100
So we get income from
our products.

00:11:12.100 --> 00:11:13.990
Not very much because at
the end of the day,

00:11:13.990 --> 00:11:15.170
our currency is impact.

00:11:15.170 --> 00:11:17.080
It's not financial return.

00:11:17.080 --> 00:11:18.430
We believe that our partners
should have

00:11:18.430 --> 00:11:19.560
some skin in the game.

00:11:19.560 --> 00:11:22.270
And just like we want to sell
our products to end users, we

00:11:22.270 --> 00:11:25.300
think that we should also sell
our product to partners.

00:11:25.300 --> 00:11:27.450
So we have a little bit of
income that comes in that

00:11:27.450 --> 00:11:29.760
we'll move around depending
on who our target is.

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:31.970
So for example, if we want
to sell to public rural

00:11:31.970 --> 00:11:34.180
hospitals, we might say to our
partner we'll take less

00:11:34.180 --> 00:11:37.020
royalties if you sell
more to those types

00:11:37.020 --> 00:11:39.500
of clinics and hospitals.

00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:41.880
But we do raise a little bit
of grant money to do this

00:11:41.880 --> 00:11:42.690
impact assessment.

00:11:42.690 --> 00:11:44.340
I would say, particularly now,
because we're a little bit of

00:11:44.340 --> 00:11:46.910
a young organization, we're
learning how to do impact

00:11:46.910 --> 00:11:47.450
assessment.

00:11:47.450 --> 00:11:50.460
And we don't see a lot of
examples of people doing

00:11:50.460 --> 00:11:53.610
really great impact assessment
for these types of products.

00:11:53.610 --> 00:11:55.620
So we're going through
a bit of a learning

00:11:55.620 --> 00:11:58.440
cycle on our own.

00:11:58.440 --> 00:12:00.050
OK, so I'm going to start
telling you a little

00:12:00.050 --> 00:12:01.110
bit about the knee.

00:12:01.110 --> 00:12:05.220
These are three gentleman at
the Jaipur Clinic in India.

00:12:05.220 --> 00:12:09.420
And if you're from a place
where you don't have much

00:12:09.420 --> 00:12:12.250
money, and you don't have access
to a lot of resources,

00:12:12.250 --> 00:12:14.290
and you suffer an amputation,
there aren't a lot

00:12:14.290 --> 00:12:15.720
of options for you.

00:12:15.720 --> 00:12:17.980
And you can see here,
all three of

00:12:17.980 --> 00:12:19.320
them have bamboo staffs.

00:12:19.320 --> 00:12:20.150
And that's typical.

00:12:20.150 --> 00:12:22.840
People actually won't usually
have a prosthesis at all when

00:12:22.840 --> 00:12:23.900
they come into the clinic.

00:12:23.900 --> 00:12:28.400
And so they'll be dependent
on this kind of staff.

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:32.010
So just kind of going through a
very quick overview of what

00:12:32.010 --> 00:12:35.670
the options could be, this is
a microcontroller knee.

00:12:35.670 --> 00:12:36.170
It's called the C-Leg.

00:12:36.170 --> 00:12:38.920
And I actually just saw a
gentleman with this last week.

00:12:38.920 --> 00:12:41.000
And the minimum you're going to
pay for something like this

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:42.290
is $20,000.

00:12:42.290 --> 00:12:44.850
The gentleman I talked to
paid $65,000, I heard.

00:12:44.850 --> 00:12:46.916
He and his insurance company
paid for it,

00:12:46.916 --> 00:12:48.450
which is way too much.

00:12:48.450 --> 00:12:51.370
But this is something like, for
example, US vets coming

00:12:51.370 --> 00:12:54.780
back from Iraq or Afghanistan
may be fit with.

00:12:54.780 --> 00:12:57.340
It's a smart device.

00:12:57.340 --> 00:12:58.670
This is a polycentric knee.

00:12:58.670 --> 00:13:00.520
And what that just means is
a four bar mechanism--

00:13:00.520 --> 00:13:02.100
I'm going to talk about that
again in a minute-- that more

00:13:02.100 --> 00:13:05.230
mimics the natural
walking motion.

00:13:05.230 --> 00:13:07.190
The minimum you're going to pay
for something like this is

00:13:07.190 --> 00:13:08.490
about $1,400.

00:13:08.490 --> 00:13:11.750
So a device that doesn't have
pneumatics, like some fancy

00:13:11.750 --> 00:13:17.300
stuff in there, can go $1,400
maybe up to $6,000 or $7,000.

00:13:17.300 --> 00:13:18.130
And then this--

00:13:18.130 --> 00:13:19.690
and I brought some props.

00:13:19.690 --> 00:13:21.120
Thanks, Vin.

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:24.130
This is an international
Red Cross knee.

00:13:24.130 --> 00:13:27.230
And it's single axis So you can
see it rotates around the

00:13:27.230 --> 00:13:29.310
access like a door hinge.

00:13:29.310 --> 00:13:31.780
And this is designed for poor
people, essentially.

00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:34.920
And I think, in some ways, this
kind of typifies what you

00:13:34.920 --> 00:13:37.570
saw with appropriate technology,
like lower quality

00:13:37.570 --> 00:13:39.210
for people who don't
have much.

00:13:39.210 --> 00:13:41.730
And what we know is that
in many cases, we hear

00:13:41.730 --> 00:13:43.740
anecdotally from prosthetists
we work with, is that people

00:13:43.740 --> 00:13:46.450
were in the locked position--

00:13:46.450 --> 00:13:48.140
so kind of like a peg leg.

00:13:48.140 --> 00:13:50.110
And I'll pass this around if
you want to play with it.

00:13:52.990 --> 00:13:55.400
AUDIENCE: Does it have
cushioning at all?

00:13:55.400 --> 00:13:57.650
KRISTA DONALDSON: So that would
be attached to a socket.

00:13:57.650 --> 00:13:59.050
Yeah, and actually why
don't I just show you

00:13:59.050 --> 00:14:00.882
the leg system now?

00:14:00.882 --> 00:14:02.750
AUDIENCE: You don't have
the $20,000 one?

00:14:02.750 --> 00:14:03.340
KRISTA DONALDSON: I don't.

00:14:03.340 --> 00:14:04.820
Sorry.

00:14:04.820 --> 00:14:06.980
And if I did, I don't know
if I'd pass it around.

00:14:06.980 --> 00:14:08.646
OK, so don't look at the knee
because you want that to be a

00:14:08.646 --> 00:14:09.600
surprise later.

00:14:09.600 --> 00:14:11.420
But you have a socket.

00:14:11.420 --> 00:14:12.340
And then you have an attachment

00:14:12.340 --> 00:14:14.490
that goes to a knee.

00:14:14.490 --> 00:14:17.680
And then you have a pylon
that goes to a foot.

00:14:17.680 --> 00:14:21.320
And this is actually at Jaipur
leg system if you were to go

00:14:21.320 --> 00:14:23.575
to the Jaipur Clinic in India
and be fit with something.

00:14:23.575 --> 00:14:25.530
AUDIENCE: That's the
[INAUDIBLE], right?

00:14:25.530 --> 00:14:26.835
KRISTA DONALDSON: Yes, this
is-- yes, but I don't

00:14:26.835 --> 00:14:27.396
want to ruin it.

00:14:27.396 --> 00:14:28.830
It's a surprise.

00:14:28.830 --> 00:14:31.940
So I'll pass it around,
though.

00:14:31.940 --> 00:14:33.280
I won't make you suffer again.

00:14:36.410 --> 00:14:37.190
OK, and I want to--

00:14:37.190 --> 00:14:40.480
I'm showing you a video
of a man in India.

00:14:40.480 --> 00:14:43.730
And he's wearing a single axis
knee similar to-- we actually

00:14:43.730 --> 00:14:44.980
have a single axis knee here.

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:53.640
There are hinges on both
sides of his knee.

00:14:53.640 --> 00:14:55.050
But it's essentially
a single axis.

00:14:55.050 --> 00:14:57.170
And I like this video because
when we think about

00:14:57.170 --> 00:14:59.380
prosthetics-- and the medical
device industry thinks about

00:14:59.380 --> 00:15:01.450
prosthetics, they're thinking
about here.

00:15:01.450 --> 00:15:04.350
They're thinking about generally
flat surfaces, even

00:15:04.350 --> 00:15:05.790
stairs, not a lot of dust.

00:15:05.790 --> 00:15:08.710
And that's not the reality
of much of the world.

00:15:08.710 --> 00:15:11.460
So I'm going to pass
this around.

00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:14.060
And in this video you may have
noticed, too, that even though

00:15:14.060 --> 00:15:17.360
he has the ability to flex his
knee with a single axis, he's

00:15:17.360 --> 00:15:18.840
wearing it in a locked
position.

00:15:18.840 --> 00:15:21.300
So you can see that it's
cosmetically awkward.

00:15:21.300 --> 00:15:22.820
It's clear he's an amputee.

00:15:22.820 --> 00:15:25.040
And it's physically
exhausting.

00:15:25.040 --> 00:15:27.640
And particularly with older
patients, you can just imagine

00:15:27.640 --> 00:15:29.960
what this would be like.

00:15:29.960 --> 00:15:32.870
So the problem that the original
team that looked at

00:15:32.870 --> 00:15:35.670
this is for those who suffer
above knee amputations, and

00:15:35.670 --> 00:15:37.170
you live on less than
$4 a day, there are

00:15:37.170 --> 00:15:40.880
just really no options.

00:15:40.880 --> 00:15:44.970
And what's the scale
of the need?

00:15:44.970 --> 00:15:48.895
It's about 3 million amputees a
year who need a new knee or

00:15:48.895 --> 00:15:49.900
a replacement.

00:15:49.900 --> 00:15:51.470
And so you can see the
bulk is in Asia.

00:15:51.470 --> 00:15:53.890
And we actually know that about
half a million of those

00:15:53.890 --> 00:15:56.560
are in India.

00:15:56.560 --> 00:15:59.730
And this is every year.

00:15:59.730 --> 00:16:00.790
The second--

00:16:00.790 --> 00:16:04.220
the knee that I'm passing around
now is what we call the

00:16:04.220 --> 00:16:05.530
version one, the JaipurKnee.

00:16:05.530 --> 00:16:06.960
And this was originally
developed by a group of

00:16:06.960 --> 00:16:10.460
students at Stanford that
Vin was later a part of.

00:16:10.460 --> 00:16:11.170
Oh, sorry.

00:16:11.170 --> 00:16:11.690
I'm jumping ahead.

00:16:11.690 --> 00:16:14.180
This is the single axis knee.

00:16:14.180 --> 00:16:14.910
Back up.

00:16:14.910 --> 00:16:16.590
The single axis knee that's
going around--

00:16:16.590 --> 00:16:17.470
it's the little one.

00:16:17.470 --> 00:16:18.780
Do you see the little one?

00:16:18.780 --> 00:16:19.630
OK, hold it up.

00:16:19.630 --> 00:16:20.430
Perfect.

00:16:20.430 --> 00:16:21.130
OK, this is a door hinge.

00:16:21.130 --> 00:16:24.310
This is what the Jaipur Foot
Organization had when they

00:16:24.310 --> 00:16:26.920
approached Stanford
several years ago.

00:16:26.920 --> 00:16:30.520
And then a student team, which
Vin was later a part of,

00:16:30.520 --> 00:16:32.820
developed the JaipurKnee, which
is the version one of

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:33.900
the ReMotion knee.

00:16:33.900 --> 00:16:36.960
And you can see there's
a big difference

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:38.750
in the walking motion.

00:16:38.750 --> 00:16:41.910
The first knee lacks stability
because as your weight shifts

00:16:41.910 --> 00:16:44.660
over that axis, you're going
to lose stability.

00:16:44.660 --> 00:16:45.920
And this is a polycentric
knee.

00:16:50.370 --> 00:16:51.820
One of the things I like to
mention, too, is with the

00:16:51.820 --> 00:16:53.900
design of the JaipurKnee,
which is now

00:16:53.900 --> 00:16:55.450
the ReMotion knee--

00:16:55.450 --> 00:17:00.000
it allows a lot of behaviors
that are more normal in this

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:00.940
kind of situation.

00:17:00.940 --> 00:17:02.180
A lot of people sit
cross legged.

00:17:02.180 --> 00:17:04.540
This is a young amputee named,
[? Vishen Barne ?].

00:17:04.540 --> 00:17:05.119
You can't see his knee.

00:17:05.119 --> 00:17:07.119
But he's fit with one
of our knees.

00:17:07.119 --> 00:17:09.849
There's a lot of kneeling for
prayer, squatting, all sorts

00:17:09.849 --> 00:17:12.040
of things that a lot of
Western devices aren't

00:17:12.040 --> 00:17:13.630
actually really well
designed for.

00:17:13.630 --> 00:17:17.849
And we recognize that in
the design process.

00:17:17.849 --> 00:17:20.230
So here's the version one
of the JaipurKnee.

00:17:20.230 --> 00:17:21.220
Is the leg system around?

00:17:21.220 --> 00:17:23.599
I'm going to borrow it back.

00:17:23.599 --> 00:17:24.160
Can I borrow it back?

00:17:24.160 --> 00:17:24.874
I'll give it back to you.

00:17:24.874 --> 00:17:26.540
Thanks.

00:17:26.540 --> 00:17:28.390
So what I thought I would do
is walk you through the

00:17:28.390 --> 00:17:33.345
iterations of the knee, because
now we're on the V3.

00:17:33.345 --> 00:17:37.110
But the first thing is can
anyone tell me what might be

00:17:37.110 --> 00:17:39.640
wrong if you're an amputee
and you're wearing this?

00:17:39.640 --> 00:17:40.980
AUDIENCE: The noise.

00:17:40.980 --> 00:17:42.270
KRISTA DONALDSON:
You're clicking.

00:17:42.270 --> 00:17:43.410
And no one wants to click.

00:17:43.410 --> 00:17:45.920
And if you think about it, here
there's a stigma attached

00:17:45.920 --> 00:17:46.680
to being disabled.

00:17:46.680 --> 00:17:51.140
It's that much more in many
of the places we work.

00:17:51.140 --> 00:17:56.270
And we saw this with how users
modified their knees.

00:17:56.270 --> 00:17:58.630
So here what you see is someone
actually put a bit of

00:17:58.630 --> 00:18:02.450
cloth in there to dampen
out the noise.

00:18:02.450 --> 00:18:04.280
Another thing we saw is if
you're wearing this under

00:18:04.280 --> 00:18:06.980
pants or a skirt,
is it obvious?

00:18:06.980 --> 00:18:08.630
Yeah, there's a sharp
edge here.

00:18:08.630 --> 00:18:10.410
And it was designed like
this because it

00:18:10.410 --> 00:18:11.590
was an early prototype.

00:18:11.590 --> 00:18:14.060
It works very well
for what it does.

00:18:14.060 --> 00:18:16.350
But the students hadn't
quite worked

00:18:16.350 --> 00:18:17.440
through the entire process.

00:18:17.440 --> 00:18:21.530
And we see that, too,
with patients.

00:18:21.530 --> 00:18:24.090
Wrapping things around the knee
is very common so that

00:18:24.090 --> 00:18:26.270
it's not quite so obvious when
you're sitting down that

00:18:26.270 --> 00:18:30.420
there's a prosthetic under
your skirt or pants.

00:18:30.420 --> 00:18:33.475
So that led to the Q2 knee,
which I'll give back this one.

00:18:36.330 --> 00:18:37.580
Thanks.

00:18:41.140 --> 00:18:43.300
Thanks, Vin.

00:18:43.300 --> 00:18:46.030
So a couple differences when you
pass this around you may

00:18:46.030 --> 00:18:48.090
notice that there's a--

00:18:48.090 --> 00:18:50.480
anyone know what
this rubber is?

00:18:50.480 --> 00:18:51.520
Noise dampener.

00:18:51.520 --> 00:18:54.220
This is a little loose, but I
promise it doesn't click.

00:18:54.220 --> 00:18:56.770
So there's a noise dampener
right here.

00:18:56.770 --> 00:19:01.650
Also you may notice that the
curvature is much smoother to

00:19:01.650 --> 00:19:03.810
make it not quite so obvious.

00:19:03.810 --> 00:19:05.430
The other thing you may notice,
too-- actually, you

00:19:05.430 --> 00:19:06.680
probably won't notice--
is the attachment.

00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:07.700
We changed the attachment.

00:19:07.700 --> 00:19:10.450
On this one over here, we used
an attachment that was

00:19:10.450 --> 00:19:11.920
specific to the Jaipur
Foot Organization.

00:19:11.920 --> 00:19:13.410
It was actually threaded.

00:19:13.410 --> 00:19:17.140
And that's not ideal for
alignment and for fitting.

00:19:17.140 --> 00:19:19.775
So we changed it to a more
universal adaptor, so it would

00:19:19.775 --> 00:19:21.540
be applicable to a broader
range of clinics.

00:19:28.330 --> 00:19:32.360
And now we're on the version
three, which we just launched

00:19:32.360 --> 00:19:33.220
last month.

00:19:33.220 --> 00:19:36.940
And if you're holding-- most
of you haven't held the V2

00:19:36.940 --> 00:19:38.420
yet, but you'll notice it's
a little bit heavier.

00:19:38.420 --> 00:19:39.680
It's a little bit wider.

00:19:39.680 --> 00:19:41.990
And in fact, some of the
feedback Vin got in China was

00:19:41.990 --> 00:19:45.250
like, this may be fine for you
Westerners, but it's a little

00:19:45.250 --> 00:19:48.350
bit big for us, meaning
Westerners are a little bit

00:19:48.350 --> 00:19:49.910
more overweight.

00:19:49.910 --> 00:19:53.250
So the other thing that we were
very cognizant of too is

00:19:53.250 --> 00:19:55.600
if you want to have a truly
affordable product at a high

00:19:55.600 --> 00:19:58.130
quality, it needs to be
mass produced, right?

00:19:58.130 --> 00:20:00.800
This is CNC, Computer Numerical
Control, cut out

00:20:00.800 --> 00:20:02.440
with a mill over
and over again.

00:20:02.440 --> 00:20:03.410
Not the most affordable.

00:20:03.410 --> 00:20:05.170
Not the best use of resources.

00:20:05.170 --> 00:20:06.590
What is this?

00:20:06.590 --> 00:20:08.300
Injection molded mostly.

00:20:08.300 --> 00:20:10.200
Yeah, so you'll see when
you pass it around,

00:20:10.200 --> 00:20:11.025
it's also much narrower.

00:20:11.025 --> 00:20:13.710
I think we calculated
26% narrower.

00:20:13.710 --> 00:20:18.330
And you'll see it's
much lighter.

00:20:18.330 --> 00:20:21.490
And then what we think it's
going to cost-- $80.

00:20:21.490 --> 00:20:23.984
So this knee actually is going
to field trials now, which I'm

00:20:23.984 --> 00:20:25.850
going to talk a little bit
about in a minute.

00:20:25.850 --> 00:20:29.640
But we are hoping for it to hit
the market early next year

00:20:29.640 --> 00:20:31.680
at a retail price of $80.

00:20:31.680 --> 00:20:34.060
So not a cost of goods or
a bill of materials

00:20:34.060 --> 00:20:35.562
but a retail cost.

00:20:35.562 --> 00:20:36.150
AUDIENCE: And that's
just for the--

00:20:36.150 --> 00:20:36.430
KRISTA DONALDSON: Sorry, no.

00:20:36.430 --> 00:20:36.895
That's OK.

00:20:36.895 --> 00:20:38.290
AUDIENCE: What was
the material?

00:20:38.290 --> 00:20:40.234
KRISTA DONALDSON:
Material is--

00:20:40.234 --> 00:20:41.690
VIN NARAYAN: Polycarbonate.

00:20:41.690 --> 00:20:44.030
KRISTA DONALDSON:
Polycarbonate.

00:20:44.030 --> 00:20:45.015
AUDIENCE: Is that just
for the knee itself?

00:20:45.015 --> 00:20:47.490
What about the extension
and the foot?

00:20:47.490 --> 00:20:48.410
KRISTA DONALDSON: Yeah,
that's separate.

00:20:48.410 --> 00:20:51.120
So the knee itself
would be $80.

00:20:51.120 --> 00:20:53.190
VIN NARAYAN: They're all
designed and sold modularly.

00:20:53.190 --> 00:20:55.550
So usually people are buying one
component from one place,

00:20:55.550 --> 00:20:56.240
another component.

00:20:56.240 --> 00:20:58.230
And then the way that they're
connected is standardized so

00:20:58.230 --> 00:21:02.778
you can match up products from
different manufacturers.

00:21:02.778 --> 00:21:03.235
KRISTA DONALDSON: Yes?

00:21:03.235 --> 00:21:05.980
AUDIENCE: Is the knee the
same for a child?

00:21:05.980 --> 00:21:07.140
KRISTA DONALDSON:
Great question.

00:21:07.140 --> 00:21:10.670
So I'm going to repeat the
questions for our audience

00:21:10.670 --> 00:21:11.950
that's not here.

00:21:11.950 --> 00:21:13.650
The question is is the
knee the same for an

00:21:13.650 --> 00:21:15.160
adult versus a child?

00:21:15.160 --> 00:21:16.250
It's based on weight.

00:21:16.250 --> 00:21:19.180
So depending on how large
the child is, they

00:21:19.180 --> 00:21:20.020
can wear our knee.

00:21:20.020 --> 00:21:22.320
But actually, one of the things
we're interested in is

00:21:22.320 --> 00:21:24.950
redesigning the knee at another
point for children,

00:21:24.950 --> 00:21:26.720
too, or having a second knee.

00:21:26.720 --> 00:21:28.580
That's a great question.

00:21:28.580 --> 00:21:30.070
Any others before we move on?

00:21:30.070 --> 00:21:30.520
Sure.

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:32.534
AUDIENCE: Does the $80 cover
the marginal cost of

00:21:32.534 --> 00:21:34.202
manufacturing and
distribution?

00:21:34.202 --> 00:21:35.890
KRISTA DONALDSON: Yes.

00:21:35.890 --> 00:21:40.110
Yeah and actually we're hoping
we can get it lower.

00:21:40.110 --> 00:21:42.210
I think one of the critical
things in this field is people

00:21:42.210 --> 00:21:43.560
get really excited
about a product.

00:21:43.560 --> 00:21:45.400
And they put out a price based
on how much they think it's

00:21:45.400 --> 00:21:46.870
going to cost to make it.

00:21:46.870 --> 00:21:49.700
And once they figure out
distribution costs, and

00:21:49.700 --> 00:21:53.380
tariffs, and fees--

00:21:53.380 --> 00:21:55.390
mystery fees, and all sorts of
things getting them into

00:21:55.390 --> 00:21:56.240
countries--

00:21:56.240 --> 00:21:57.510
the price goes up a lot.

00:21:57.510 --> 00:21:59.820
And from my standpoint, one of
the things I really learned

00:21:59.820 --> 00:22:03.080
working in Kenya, is consumer
trust is so critical.

00:22:03.080 --> 00:22:05.890
And if you put out a price that
something's going to be

00:22:05.890 --> 00:22:08.980
$80, but you come back and you
say, no, actually it's going

00:22:08.980 --> 00:22:13.150
to be $200, you've already
had one level of

00:22:13.150 --> 00:22:14.590
trust that you've lost.

00:22:14.590 --> 00:22:17.300
So we built in margins
based on the best

00:22:17.300 --> 00:22:18.020
research we could do.

00:22:18.020 --> 00:22:21.190
And then we put a little extra
in for what we don't know,

00:22:21.190 --> 00:22:23.050
which we think will
be something.

00:22:23.050 --> 00:22:25.870
AUDIENCE: Were there any trade
offs in terms of the product

00:22:25.870 --> 00:22:29.710
lifetime, like life span in
terms of the reduction in

00:22:29.710 --> 00:22:31.820
costs and whether or not that
means that they would have to

00:22:31.820 --> 00:22:35.520
replace it sooner or if it's
comparable to what the

00:22:35.520 --> 00:22:36.655
previous ones were?

00:22:36.655 --> 00:22:37.880
KRISTA DONALDSON: Well,
there are standards

00:22:37.880 --> 00:22:38.510
that we have to meet.

00:22:38.510 --> 00:22:40.180
And I'll let Vin give you
the detailed answer.

00:22:40.180 --> 00:22:42.810
But essentially, there are
standards that say what the

00:22:42.810 --> 00:22:46.640
lifetime of a product must be.

00:22:46.640 --> 00:22:49.630
VIN NARAYAN: Yeah, so we hit the
exact same lifetime that

00:22:49.630 --> 00:22:50.550
Western devices do.

00:22:50.550 --> 00:22:53.480
In fact, I think we go a little
bit further, because to

00:22:53.480 --> 00:22:56.520
hit that life that they state,
they also say you can't get it

00:22:56.520 --> 00:22:58.606
wet, you can't use it in dirty
conditions, you have to

00:22:58.606 --> 00:23:01.010
service it every six months,
which isn't really a reality

00:23:01.010 --> 00:23:02.390
for the context we're
working in.

00:23:02.390 --> 00:23:04.410
And so we're designing it to
hit that same lifetime but

00:23:04.410 --> 00:23:06.940
without any of those
requirements on top.

00:23:06.940 --> 00:23:09.270
KRISTA DONALDSON: One of the
things we learned is

00:23:09.270 --> 00:23:12.490
obviously, like Vin said, the
testing is kind of based on

00:23:12.490 --> 00:23:13.690
Western wear.

00:23:13.690 --> 00:23:15.500
And one of the things we really
had to think about

00:23:15.500 --> 00:23:17.150
during the product
specifications is well,

00:23:17.150 --> 00:23:20.360
actually what is our user
going to be faced with?

00:23:20.360 --> 00:23:23.640
And we know there's a huge rural
population that would be

00:23:23.640 --> 00:23:24.350
using our knee.

00:23:24.350 --> 00:23:25.160
They're going to be in fields.

00:23:25.160 --> 00:23:25.770
It's going to be wet.

00:23:25.770 --> 00:23:28.440
It's going to be dusty like you
saw with the gentleman,

00:23:28.440 --> 00:23:29.590
the rough terrain.

00:23:29.590 --> 00:23:32.520
And so how do we make sure that
when we do the mechanical

00:23:32.520 --> 00:23:34.460
testing here we account
for that?

00:23:34.460 --> 00:23:37.010
Because we don't want to be
discovering that when it's on

00:23:37.010 --> 00:23:38.930
our test users, right?

00:23:38.930 --> 00:23:45.490
So these are all things that
we're trying to stay ahead of.

00:23:45.490 --> 00:23:49.540
So this is Kamal, the young
man earlier who you saw

00:23:49.540 --> 00:23:50.570
working on our knee.

00:23:50.570 --> 00:23:52.710
And he actually climbed
a tree later.

00:23:52.710 --> 00:23:55.740
So we love this picture
of him.

00:23:55.740 --> 00:23:59.550
So I had mentioned earlier how
you have to measure to know if

00:23:59.550 --> 00:24:00.490
you're hitting impact.

00:24:00.490 --> 00:24:03.060
And so with all of our projects,
we're very clear

00:24:03.060 --> 00:24:04.300
about what the goals are.

00:24:04.300 --> 00:24:07.410
And with this project it's
to re-mobilize people,

00:24:07.410 --> 00:24:09.330
re-mobilize above
knee amputees.

00:24:09.330 --> 00:24:12.540
And we have usually two to three
meta indicators we use

00:24:12.540 --> 00:24:14.140
with all of our projects.

00:24:14.140 --> 00:24:17.060
So for the knee project we look
at number of amputees

00:24:17.060 --> 00:24:18.520
fit, which is a little
bit of an output.

00:24:18.520 --> 00:24:23.820
For example, just how many knees
are there being worn?

00:24:23.820 --> 00:24:25.965
And then just to kind of give
you a little bit of color is

00:24:25.965 --> 00:24:28.600
that this knee is now in
12 different countries.

00:24:28.600 --> 00:24:33.070
We have a knee in 12 different
countries, mostly the V1 knee.

00:24:33.070 --> 00:24:36.350
But I think the really
meaningful impact number is

00:24:36.350 --> 00:24:37.020
compliance.

00:24:37.020 --> 00:24:39.900
And compliance means is the
amputee still wearing the knee

00:24:39.900 --> 00:24:44.490
six months later, because that
more tells you are you really

00:24:44.490 --> 00:24:47.760
truly re-mobilizing people, with
the goal being increased

00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:50.490
income, increased access,
increased

00:24:50.490 --> 00:24:52.010
participation in life.

00:24:52.010 --> 00:24:55.670
And our compliance rate is about
79%, which is great.

00:24:55.670 --> 00:24:57.420
It's not good enough,
we don't think.

00:24:57.420 --> 00:25:00.250
But as a sense of perspective,
the ICRC knee

00:25:00.250 --> 00:25:02.340
system is about 65%.

00:25:02.340 --> 00:25:05.560
And we have learned
through getting

00:25:05.560 --> 00:25:07.130
feedback on the product--

00:25:07.130 --> 00:25:08.680
and who's got-- where's
the leg system?

00:25:08.680 --> 00:25:10.530
VIN NARAYAN: Actually,
the version--

00:25:10.530 --> 00:25:11.540
the previous JaipurKnee.

00:25:11.540 --> 00:25:12.430
KRISTA DONALDSON: Oh,
the previous?

00:25:12.430 --> 00:25:13.140
Sorry, OK.

00:25:13.140 --> 00:25:14.160
So also single axis.

00:25:14.160 --> 00:25:16.930
So thank you.

00:25:16.930 --> 00:25:18.690
Has anyone got the leg system?

00:25:18.690 --> 00:25:19.540
It's right here.

00:25:19.540 --> 00:25:21.460
One of the things that we've
actually found is that

00:25:21.460 --> 00:25:24.640
compliance, one of the things
that hurts us, when you talk

00:25:24.640 --> 00:25:27.990
to amputees and you say, what
would you change about it,

00:25:27.990 --> 00:25:28.770
usually the first thing
they would say

00:25:28.770 --> 00:25:30.600
is, I'm not an amputee.

00:25:30.600 --> 00:25:31.340
I'm not an amputee.

00:25:31.340 --> 00:25:34.540
But the second thing they would
say is the socket gives

00:25:34.540 --> 00:25:35.400
a lot of problems.

00:25:35.400 --> 00:25:36.800
So when you see this compliance
number, it's

00:25:36.800 --> 00:25:39.260
actually are you still wearing
your leg system.

00:25:39.260 --> 00:25:41.710
What's been interesting for us
if you think back that our

00:25:41.710 --> 00:25:44.370
goal is re-mobilizing people,
it's made us think about what

00:25:44.370 --> 00:25:47.060
could be our potential
next projects.

00:25:47.060 --> 00:25:48.220
So it's not just
about the knee.

00:25:48.220 --> 00:25:51.930
We know that the socket has a
lot of issues, too, because

00:25:51.930 --> 00:25:54.090
people's residual limb
changes over time.

00:25:54.090 --> 00:25:56.650
It changes just based on
a variety of things.

00:25:56.650 --> 00:25:59.850
And blistering is
a real issue.

00:25:59.850 --> 00:26:00.990
I'll give this back to you.

00:26:00.990 --> 00:26:02.240
Thanks.

00:26:04.490 --> 00:26:09.630
So besides the numbers, I
thought I would share a few

00:26:09.630 --> 00:26:10.980
patient stories.

00:26:10.980 --> 00:26:13.120
And this is a young woman
named Pernima.

00:26:13.120 --> 00:26:15.440
And she lost her leg
in a car accident.

00:26:15.440 --> 00:26:16.670
It was actually fairly tragic.

00:26:16.670 --> 00:26:19.380
And she lost her
little brother.

00:26:19.380 --> 00:26:21.630
One of the things that's really
amazing about her, to

00:26:21.630 --> 00:26:24.770
me, I think as a female engineer
particularly, is that

00:26:24.770 --> 00:26:27.920
when she was re-mobilized with
one of our knees, she said to

00:26:27.920 --> 00:26:29.760
us, I want to go back to school,
and I want to become

00:26:29.760 --> 00:26:30.810
an engineer.

00:26:30.810 --> 00:26:33.680
And I love that story, because
at the end of the day, we

00:26:33.680 --> 00:26:36.250
don't necessarily want people
like us and people based in

00:26:36.250 --> 00:26:39.460
the West working on projects
to solve the problems but

00:26:39.460 --> 00:26:41.910
people like Pernima addressing
some of the

00:26:41.910 --> 00:26:43.250
issues she sees locally.

00:26:46.030 --> 00:26:47.730
This is also another
funny story.

00:26:47.730 --> 00:26:50.670
So Andreas on the left is
wearing our version two knee.

00:26:50.670 --> 00:26:53.070
The version two is actually only
fit on five amputees down

00:26:53.070 --> 00:26:56.260
in Ecuador because we were
testing the noise dampener and

00:26:56.260 --> 00:26:58.230
things like that before moving
on to wanting to

00:26:58.230 --> 00:27:00.150
injection mold it.

00:27:00.150 --> 00:27:03.070
But Andreas had lost his leg
in a motorcycle accident.

00:27:03.070 --> 00:27:05.300
And I'm laughing because one
of the things he was most

00:27:05.300 --> 00:27:08.040
excited about being re-mobilized
was to get back

00:27:08.040 --> 00:27:09.190
on the motorcycle.

00:27:09.190 --> 00:27:14.220
So here you see him here quite
happy to have his new knee

00:27:14.220 --> 00:27:17.070
with his friend.

00:27:17.070 --> 00:27:19.950
So to give you a sense of where
we are now with the

00:27:19.950 --> 00:27:21.520
knee, this is--

00:27:21.520 --> 00:27:22.990
I had mentioned the
12 countries--

00:27:22.990 --> 00:27:24.650
and hopefully these
dots add up to 12.

00:27:24.650 --> 00:27:27.350
But this is where our knee is
in use right now through our

00:27:27.350 --> 00:27:29.040
partnership with the
Jaipur Foot Clinic.

00:27:29.040 --> 00:27:31.160
So they actually have a central

00:27:31.160 --> 00:27:32.690
clinic in Jaipur, India.

00:27:32.690 --> 00:27:36.330
They have 22 other clinics
around India, Delhi--

00:27:36.330 --> 00:27:38.480
basically name your major city,
and they have a smaller

00:27:38.480 --> 00:27:39.310
clinic there.

00:27:39.310 --> 00:27:41.680
But they also do camps
in other places.

00:27:41.680 --> 00:27:44.490
And so they fit the version
one knee in all

00:27:44.490 --> 00:27:48.230
of these other countries.

00:27:48.230 --> 00:27:50.940
As I mentioned, we're just
starting our version three

00:27:50.940 --> 00:27:51.810
field trials.

00:27:51.810 --> 00:27:54.260
And we're doing that in five
different countries.

00:27:54.260 --> 00:27:57.010
As of last week, Vin just
returned from Indonesia, two

00:27:57.010 --> 00:28:00.100
clinics in Indonesia that
are trying out our

00:28:00.100 --> 00:28:03.230
version three knee.

00:28:03.230 --> 00:28:05.820
And here's a picture, actually,
of the first amputee

00:28:05.820 --> 00:28:07.730
fit in Bali.

00:28:07.730 --> 00:28:08.570
And we love his smile.

00:28:08.570 --> 00:28:11.590
And actually this is our
colleague, Sam, behind him

00:28:11.590 --> 00:28:12.540
checking out alignment.

00:28:12.540 --> 00:28:15.970
And what we're really looking
for in these field trials is

00:28:15.970 --> 00:28:19.420
does it work essentially, do we
see an increase in income,

00:28:19.420 --> 00:28:22.610
increase in quality of life, but
also are there any things

00:28:22.610 --> 00:28:25.530
that we need to know before we
really scale up into mass

00:28:25.530 --> 00:28:26.700
production.

00:28:26.700 --> 00:28:28.280
Are there any feature tweaks,
or anything that

00:28:28.280 --> 00:28:29.680
we need to be changing?

00:28:29.680 --> 00:28:32.000
And so we have a six month study
running at each of these

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:33.810
sites where we're getting
feedback on

00:28:33.810 --> 00:28:35.060
all of these things.

00:28:37.840 --> 00:28:40.840
So one of the things I'd like
to mention too, even though

00:28:40.840 --> 00:28:44.080
this project, we haven't done
a lot of PR about it--

00:28:44.080 --> 00:28:46.385
Stanford did in the early days
with the version one, but

00:28:46.385 --> 00:28:49.990
we've gotten inquiries from all
of these different places.

00:28:49.990 --> 00:28:51.320
And what's been really
interesting to me is that

00:28:51.320 --> 00:28:54.730
we've also gotten inquiries
from the US, patients who

00:28:54.730 --> 00:28:57.630
either don't have insurance or
people, for example, who have

00:28:57.630 --> 00:29:00.330
a very active lifestyle, often
vets, who come back.

00:29:00.330 --> 00:29:02.620
And they don't want to be using
that $20,000 knee to go

00:29:02.620 --> 00:29:05.550
to the beach or to
go kayaking.

00:29:05.550 --> 00:29:08.420
So I think a take away for
us is that there's a need

00:29:08.420 --> 00:29:12.740
globally, not just in our target
populations where they

00:29:12.740 --> 00:29:16.640
live on less than $4 a day.

00:29:16.640 --> 00:29:18.650
So I thought I would share a few
lessons learned, because I

00:29:18.650 --> 00:29:19.700
don't want you to think
that we have

00:29:19.700 --> 00:29:20.700
everything figured out.

00:29:20.700 --> 00:29:21.740
We're far from that.

00:29:21.740 --> 00:29:24.320
And just to tell you what this
is because you saw this

00:29:24.320 --> 00:29:27.250
earlier, these are some of the
early sketches that went into

00:29:27.250 --> 00:29:28.700
the design of the V3.

00:29:28.700 --> 00:29:31.810
We feel very strongly that
people should be proud of

00:29:31.810 --> 00:29:33.070
their prosthetic.

00:29:33.070 --> 00:29:35.260
And at least, it should fit
with them in their life.

00:29:35.260 --> 00:29:38.430
So we worked with a volunteer
industrial designer who did

00:29:38.430 --> 00:29:43.950
these renderings that led
to the V3 design.

00:29:43.950 --> 00:29:47.060
So this is a picture of a
prosthetics clinic in Kenya

00:29:47.060 --> 00:29:49.910
that I went to go
visit last year.

00:29:49.910 --> 00:29:51.770
And actually I was there for
one of our other projects.

00:29:51.770 --> 00:29:54.415
But I wanted to find out about
this clinic and how

00:29:54.415 --> 00:29:55.580
it worked in Kenya.

00:29:55.580 --> 00:29:57.190
Couldn't get them to
answer the phone,

00:29:57.190 --> 00:29:58.260
which is not unusual.

00:29:58.260 --> 00:29:59.260
So we just dropped in.

00:29:59.260 --> 00:30:02.830
And four skilled processes,
which is not necessarily

00:30:02.830 --> 00:30:04.520
unusual, but it's pretty cool.

00:30:04.520 --> 00:30:06.690
One of the big challenges we
see with getting people

00:30:06.690 --> 00:30:08.970
re-mobilized is they might
have-- for example, in Haiti

00:30:08.970 --> 00:30:11.350
they might have a lot of
donated technology.

00:30:11.350 --> 00:30:12.200
But they don't have the skilled

00:30:12.200 --> 00:30:14.250
processes to fit people.

00:30:14.250 --> 00:30:16.840
But these processes, four
processors, were really busy

00:30:16.840 --> 00:30:18.680
not doing much of anything.

00:30:18.680 --> 00:30:22.170
And the reason was because they
could not get all the

00:30:22.170 --> 00:30:24.090
components to that leg
system that we talked

00:30:24.090 --> 00:30:28.420
about into the clinic.

00:30:28.420 --> 00:30:31.160
So they were waiting on
components to come in.

00:30:31.160 --> 00:30:33.350
And in the meantime, even though
they had amputees that

00:30:33.350 --> 00:30:36.400
needed to be fit, they weren't
actually fitting people.

00:30:36.400 --> 00:30:39.760
So a lesson learned-- well
actually re-learned, because I

00:30:39.760 --> 00:30:42.200
mentioned this came up with one
of my lessons learned in

00:30:42.200 --> 00:30:44.880
Kenya-- is impact is more
than the product.

00:30:44.880 --> 00:30:46.990
It's about getting the product
to people and getting the

00:30:46.990 --> 00:30:48.720
product to people who need it.

00:30:48.720 --> 00:30:51.890
And going back to our model of
market driven, one of the

00:30:51.890 --> 00:30:53.800
reasons why we're market driven
is because if people

00:30:53.800 --> 00:30:55.400
see value in your product,
they're going to buy it.

00:30:55.400 --> 00:30:56.880
And if they see value in
your product, they're

00:30:56.880 --> 00:30:57.580
going to use it.

00:30:57.580 --> 00:30:59.290
But you have to get
it to them.

00:30:59.290 --> 00:31:03.950
So another kind of reminder take
away is really truly if

