model in addition to the

00:42:30.390 --> 00:42:33.240
product and very much using
a design process

00:42:33.240 --> 00:42:34.815
for that whole system.

00:42:38.200 --> 00:42:39.700
AUDIENCE: I just had a question,
because I really

00:42:39.700 --> 00:42:42.410
admire the kind of structure
you have that's very

00:42:42.410 --> 00:42:43.270
sustainable.

00:42:43.270 --> 00:42:46.950
And I think inherent in that
structure is a focus on the

00:42:46.950 --> 00:42:48.800
end user, which I really like.

00:42:48.800 --> 00:42:53.220
So my question is are there
other companies or nonprofits

00:42:53.220 --> 00:42:55.680
that you kind of modeled
this after?

00:42:55.680 --> 00:42:58.740
And were there any lesson
learns in the overall

00:42:58.740 --> 00:43:02.410
structure that you guys chose
for your nonprofit?

00:43:02.410 --> 00:43:04.100
KRISTA DONALDSON: I'll try and
answer that delicately.

00:43:04.100 --> 00:43:06.870
I feel like a lot of the model
and the approach that D-Rev

00:43:06.870 --> 00:43:11.690
takes is recognition of where,
in many ways, the aid sector

00:43:11.690 --> 00:43:13.290
has failed people.

00:43:13.290 --> 00:43:15.122
And I hate to say that, because
I don't want to put

00:43:15.122 --> 00:43:15.770
everyone in a basket.

00:43:15.770 --> 00:43:16.820
Because there's a lot
of great work

00:43:16.820 --> 00:43:18.110
that's obviously happening.

00:43:18.110 --> 00:43:20.730
But a lot of these things-- like
I saw in Kenya, and Iraq,

00:43:20.730 --> 00:43:21.940
and some of the other
places I worked.

00:43:21.940 --> 00:43:25.210
And I know Vin has a lot of
experience in working with

00:43:25.210 --> 00:43:25.890
prosthetics clinics.

00:43:25.890 --> 00:43:28.920
And really, I feel like if we're
not designing for the

00:43:28.920 --> 00:43:32.430
end user and for the impact,
then what are we doing?

00:43:32.430 --> 00:43:35.510
So everything, I feel like, when
we're making decisions,

00:43:35.510 --> 00:43:38.180
it all comes back to what's
best for impact and what's

00:43:38.180 --> 00:43:39.310
best for the end user.

00:43:39.310 --> 00:43:42.650
And I'll also say one of the
challenges we've had is, like

00:43:42.650 --> 00:43:44.840
I had mentioned earlier, is
getting our impact assessment

00:43:44.840 --> 00:43:45.400
up and running.

00:43:45.400 --> 00:43:49.100
Because the impact assessment
kind of traditional model is

00:43:49.100 --> 00:43:51.650
focused, for example, in health
on DLAYs, Disability

00:43:51.650 --> 00:43:53.830
Life Adjusted Years, which is
kind of meaningless to end

00:43:53.830 --> 00:43:54.860
users and doctors.

00:43:54.860 --> 00:43:57.170
It's a very global
health thing.

00:43:57.170 --> 00:44:01.570
And we feel like if we're
focused on end users, we need

00:44:01.570 --> 00:44:03.460
to really understand what
their needs are, and

00:44:03.460 --> 00:44:05.400
understanding if they're using
the product, and how many

00:44:05.400 --> 00:44:06.460
babies are using it.

00:44:06.460 --> 00:44:07.290
And one of the things--

00:44:07.290 --> 00:44:09.020
I wanted to keep the focus
on the knee today.

00:44:09.020 --> 00:44:11.670
But Brilliance, we can actually
track the number of

00:44:11.670 --> 00:44:14.660
babies that are being treated by
the device, which helps us

00:44:14.660 --> 00:44:15.410
with impact assessment.

00:44:15.410 --> 00:44:17.290
And so we're always trying to
figure out how to do things

00:44:17.290 --> 00:44:20.940
very efficiently, because we
don't fit into the mold of a

00:44:20.940 --> 00:44:22.890
traditional product nonprofit.

00:44:22.890 --> 00:44:24.150
So if you see other groups--

00:44:24.150 --> 00:44:26.180
I mean there's a lot of great
groups out there.

00:44:26.180 --> 00:44:28.960
But if you see other groups,
too, we're all ears, because I

00:44:28.960 --> 00:44:31.040
feel like we've definitely
struggled through a lot of

00:44:31.040 --> 00:44:32.510
lessons learned,
as you can see.

00:44:32.510 --> 00:44:34.740
And we're changing our path.

00:44:34.740 --> 00:44:37.600
But as much as possible, we try
and learn from what other

00:44:37.600 --> 00:44:39.000
groups have been through.

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:40.370
VIN NARAYAN: I think it's also
important to note that the

00:44:40.370 --> 00:44:43.280
approach depends on what
products you're working on.

00:44:43.280 --> 00:44:45.112
It's not a one fit approach,
as Krista

00:44:45.112 --> 00:44:46.320
mentioned, for every nonprofit.

00:44:46.320 --> 00:44:49.090
So just like we had to pick the
approach that we think is

00:44:49.090 --> 00:44:51.880
most likely to lead to impact,
we also have to pick products

00:44:51.880 --> 00:44:53.640
and projects that best
fit our approach.

00:44:53.640 --> 00:44:55.280
We'll never do a vaccine
product.

00:44:55.280 --> 00:44:56.050
That's not going to happen.

00:44:56.050 --> 00:44:57.820
And that's not to say
that this is the

00:44:57.820 --> 00:44:59.350
right way to do vaccines.

00:44:59.350 --> 00:45:01.970
But we pick products that work
well with our approach and

00:45:01.970 --> 00:45:03.830
that we think can scale
easily that way.

00:45:03.830 --> 00:45:05.380
KRISTA DONALDSON: I would also
add that we're very pragmatic

00:45:05.380 --> 00:45:06.700
at the end of the day.

00:45:06.700 --> 00:45:08.190
We're 10 people.

00:45:08.190 --> 00:45:13.000
So we're very clear about what
we can and what we can't do.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:15.490
With jaundice, the biggest need
is actually screening.

00:45:15.490 --> 00:45:17.610
But that takes a huge
capital investment.

00:45:17.610 --> 00:45:19.810
It would take probably about
five more staff.

00:45:19.810 --> 00:45:22.380
So we can't do that until we're
at a different stage.

00:45:22.380 --> 00:45:24.470
We also felt like it didn't make
sense to have screening

00:45:24.470 --> 00:45:27.180
before there's treatment
in place.

00:45:27.180 --> 00:45:31.140
So I think one of the things
that I feel like is one of our

00:45:31.140 --> 00:45:33.690
core strengths is that we have
the ability to say, no, we

00:45:33.690 --> 00:45:34.710
actually can't do this.

00:45:34.710 --> 00:45:38.180
It's beyond our scope, our skill
set, our everything.

00:45:38.180 --> 00:45:41.300
And this is best for another
organization.

00:45:41.300 --> 00:45:43.080
Now that we have a little bit
more impact, we have groups

00:45:43.080 --> 00:45:43.470
coming to us.

00:45:43.470 --> 00:45:46.010
And we try and match them with
groups that can carry the

00:45:46.010 --> 00:45:49.290
projects forward.

00:45:49.290 --> 00:45:51.510
AUDIENCE: That was a good
segue for my question.

