First of all, I think
you guys are doing

00:45:53.140 --> 00:45:54.270
really spectacular work.

00:45:54.270 --> 00:45:56.370
And this has been really
awesome to just

00:45:56.370 --> 00:45:58.540
hear from you live.

00:45:58.540 --> 00:46:00.330
My question was actually about
impact evaluation.

00:46:00.330 --> 00:46:03.970
So you mentioned that you're
kind of setting up how you're

00:46:03.970 --> 00:46:06.130
going to be evaluating
impact going forward.

00:46:06.130 --> 00:46:09.320
So I just wanted to get your
thoughts on where you're

00:46:09.320 --> 00:46:12.280
focusing on for Brilliance or
some of the other products

00:46:12.280 --> 00:46:14.630
that you're working with.

00:46:14.630 --> 00:46:17.550
And I know there are a couple
of nonprofits that focus

00:46:17.550 --> 00:46:20.990
solely on providing impact
evaluation expertise to other

00:46:20.990 --> 00:46:21.670
non-profits.

00:46:21.670 --> 00:46:24.600
So is that a direction
you're looking for?

00:46:24.600 --> 00:46:26.080
KRISTA DONALDSON: We looked
at that, yeah.

00:46:26.080 --> 00:46:27.610
So how about I give
the meta answer.

00:46:27.610 --> 00:46:30.130
And then I'd love Vin to talk
about the trials a little bit,

00:46:30.130 --> 00:46:32.370
because we've done, what I think
is, an incredible job of

00:46:32.370 --> 00:46:34.570
setting up data collection
with the field trials.

00:46:34.570 --> 00:46:37.230
So on the meta levels, we've
tried to work with some of the

00:46:37.230 --> 00:46:39.810
very well known impact
assessment groups.

00:46:39.810 --> 00:46:42.130
But one of the challenges we've
run into is that we're

00:46:42.130 --> 00:46:43.270
very impact focused.

00:46:43.270 --> 00:46:44.710
And a lot of those
groups are led by

00:46:44.710 --> 00:46:46.380
academics who need to publish.

00:46:46.380 --> 00:46:49.140
And there's not necessarily an
overlap in those two things.

00:46:49.140 --> 00:46:51.120
So we've said, can you please
take our project?

00:46:51.120 --> 00:46:52.560
We need third party
evaluation.

00:46:52.560 --> 00:46:54.680
We would actually love third
party evaluation and for you

00:46:54.680 --> 00:46:56.390
to teach us what you're
doing so that we can

00:46:56.390 --> 00:46:57.800
do it in the future.

00:46:57.800 --> 00:47:00.090
and we haven't been
successful so far.

00:47:00.090 --> 00:47:02.390
And that's something that I
actually know a board member

00:47:02.390 --> 00:47:02.830
on one of those.

00:47:02.830 --> 00:47:05.270
And I've been bugging
him about it.

00:47:05.270 --> 00:47:10.360
I think again we try and keep
things very pragmatic.

00:47:10.360 --> 00:47:13.250
But I would love you to talk
about maybe the knee.

00:47:13.250 --> 00:47:15.610
VIN NARAYAN: So I think one of
the challenges when we were--

00:47:15.610 --> 00:47:17.690
so we just set up this
100 unit trial.

00:47:17.690 --> 00:47:19.300
And it's going to be running for
the next six months or so.

00:47:19.300 --> 00:47:21.920
And one of the challenges with
looking for an outside impact

00:47:21.920 --> 00:47:25.740
group was that we needed such
a specific set of evaluation

00:47:25.740 --> 00:47:29.230
that I think it was going to
be difficult to set that up

00:47:29.230 --> 00:47:30.380
for such a short
period of time.

00:47:30.380 --> 00:47:34.180
So what we did was really look
at what we think were the best

00:47:34.180 --> 00:47:36.230
practices that some other groups
were doing and try to

00:47:36.230 --> 00:47:37.560
implement that in
our approach.

00:47:37.560 --> 00:47:41.770
So for example, we looked at
well established prosthetics

00:47:41.770 --> 00:47:44.460
evaluation metrics, and gait
metrics, and tried to take

00:47:44.460 --> 00:47:47.130
questions from existing studies
that could be vetted

00:47:47.130 --> 00:47:50.390
and incorporate that into ours,
and then sort of combine

00:47:50.390 --> 00:47:52.710
that with other things that
maybe aren't part of the

00:47:52.710 --> 00:47:55.250
traditional prosthetics study
like what is the change in

00:47:55.250 --> 00:47:57.800
income six months later, or
things about socioeconomic

00:47:57.800 --> 00:48:00.630
status, and how those are
changing, as well as talking

00:48:00.630 --> 00:48:02.370
to some other nonprofit groups,
and looking at the

00:48:02.370 --> 00:48:03.560
impact work that they're
doing, and how

00:48:03.560 --> 00:48:04.800
they're doing it.

00:48:04.800 --> 00:48:07.710
A good example is that we met
with one really amazing group

00:48:07.710 --> 00:48:10.730
in New York that uses Dropbox
actually to sync.

00:48:10.730 --> 00:48:12.002
KRISTA DONALDSON: It's the
little details that make all

00:48:12.002 --> 00:48:13.470
the difference.

00:48:13.470 --> 00:48:14.930
VIN NARAYAN: And it was like
such a why didn't we think of

00:48:14.930 --> 00:48:15.240
that kind of moment.

00:48:15.240 --> 00:48:15.970
KRISTA DONALDSON: Because
we were having

00:48:15.970 --> 00:48:17.390
them fill out forms.

00:48:17.390 --> 00:48:19.280
And we're like no, they can
just load it into Dropbox.

00:48:19.280 --> 00:48:20.550
And then it magically appears.

00:48:20.550 --> 00:48:21.770
VIN NARAYAN: Yeah, like
let Dropbox do the

00:48:21.770 --> 00:48:23.650
hard part of it.

00:48:23.650 --> 00:48:24.400
AUDIENCE: Or Docs.

00:48:24.400 --> 00:48:25.981
KRISTA DONALDSON: Yeah,
we'll move to that.

00:48:25.981 --> 00:48:27.920
Much better--

00:48:27.920 --> 00:48:29.220
Docs.

00:48:29.220 --> 00:48:30.960
VIN NARAYAN: Stage two.

00:48:30.960 --> 00:48:31.390
KRISTA DONALDSON:
That's right.

00:48:31.390 --> 00:48:34.130
We're getting better
and better.

00:48:34.130 --> 00:48:36.320
VIN NARAYAN: But little things
like that and just kind of see

00:48:36.320 --> 00:48:38.410
what people were doing and
incorporating the best

00:48:38.410 --> 00:48:41.780
practices and making it fit our
approach really well was,

00:48:41.780 --> 00:48:44.670
I think, a really good
lesson learned.

00:48:44.670 --> 00:48:46.660
KRISTA DONALDSON: Yeah, the
other thing I would add is

00:48:46.660 --> 00:48:48.930
thanks to the SEED program
at Stanford.

