00:51:21.440 --> 00:51:23.070
Or are you interested in
buying Brilliance?

00:51:23.070 --> 00:51:25.260
And we're just starting
to get traction now.

00:51:25.260 --> 00:51:27.060
So totally yes.

00:51:27.060 --> 00:51:28.930
AUDIENCE: You mentioned earlier
that when you're

00:51:28.930 --> 00:51:32.090
identifying projects you try
to fit it to your approach.

00:51:32.090 --> 00:51:34.870
I just wanted to hear more about
what other factors you

00:51:34.870 --> 00:51:38.480
consider when thinking
about new projects.

00:51:38.480 --> 00:51:41.220
Do you kind of have people
approach you, or do you do

00:51:41.220 --> 00:51:45.650
kind of base from
need finding.

00:51:45.650 --> 00:51:47.280
How does that look like?

00:51:47.280 --> 00:51:48.510
KRISTA DONALDSON: A
bit of everything.

00:51:48.510 --> 00:51:51.320
So we have a lot of new needs
that come into us.

00:51:51.320 --> 00:51:52.330
People approach us.

00:51:52.330 --> 00:51:54.730
The Brilliance project started
with a doctor coming.

00:51:54.730 --> 00:51:57.040
The knee started with the Jaipur
Foot Organization going

00:51:57.040 --> 00:51:58.390
to Stanford.

00:51:58.390 --> 00:52:01.090
Because we're in so many
hospitals and clinics, we see

00:52:01.090 --> 00:52:01.760
a lot of things.

00:52:01.760 --> 00:52:04.690
And we talk to doctors, and
we learn about new things.

00:52:04.690 --> 00:52:06.450
It's been really interesting.

00:52:06.450 --> 00:52:09.190
With people coming to us with
needs, often if they're

00:52:09.190 --> 00:52:11.770
Westerners, they're coming
to us with solutions.

00:52:11.770 --> 00:52:13.450
They're not actually coming
to us with needs.

00:52:13.450 --> 00:52:17.490
So they'll come and say,
oh, this thing is

00:52:17.490 --> 00:52:18.530
going to solve x.

00:52:18.530 --> 00:52:20.530
And I'm like, well, what's
the problem?

00:52:20.530 --> 00:52:23.320
And what's also really
interesting is if you dig into

00:52:23.320 --> 00:52:25.880
the problem, it's often
not a problem.

00:52:25.880 --> 00:52:28.120
And so we do a lot of due
diligence, too, to really

00:52:28.120 --> 00:52:29.160
understand the problem.

00:52:29.160 --> 00:52:31.300
And one of my favorite
professors at Stanford used to

00:52:31.300 --> 00:52:33.240
always try and get your problem

00:52:33.240 --> 00:52:34.640
statement to the next level.

00:52:34.640 --> 00:52:37.260
Like if you say, oh,
I need light.

00:52:37.260 --> 00:52:38.840
Well, what do you need
the light for?

00:52:38.840 --> 00:52:40.540
Like what's the problem you're
trying to solve?

00:52:40.540 --> 00:52:45.560
Is it children need to do
homework after dark, or they

00:52:45.560 --> 00:52:48.710
want to keep their business
open after dark on a road?

00:52:48.710 --> 00:52:50.380
What's the problem you're
trying to solve?

00:52:50.380 --> 00:52:53.480
And if you can get there, that's
a good place to start.

00:52:53.480 --> 00:52:56.600
We have a framework that we
kind of run needs through.

00:52:56.600 --> 00:53:00.810
And it's everything pragmatic
from is this our sweet spot,

00:53:00.810 --> 00:53:03.410
are their key opinion leaders
who think this is an issue,

00:53:03.410 --> 00:53:05.360
will the key opinion
leaders advise us.

00:53:05.360 --> 00:53:07.760
Because as you can imagine,
getting in the door with the

00:53:07.760 --> 00:53:10.540
largest maker of neonatal
equipment in India, we just

00:53:10.540 --> 00:53:12.750
can't walk up and say hi.

00:53:12.750 --> 00:53:15.810
So are there a lot of these
conditions met that we think

00:53:15.810 --> 00:53:18.820
that we have a high success
rate of moving forward.

00:53:18.820 --> 00:53:20.820
And so that identify phase that
I showed you with the

00:53:20.820 --> 00:53:23.320
arrow, it's more than just
kind of like need

00:53:23.320 --> 00:53:25.370
identification, talking
to a few customers.

00:53:25.370 --> 00:53:28.590
It's a very intensive due
diligence process, which has

00:53:28.590 --> 00:53:30.580
been really interesting,
because, for example, funders

00:53:30.580 --> 00:53:32.690
aren't interested in throwing
money at you to just go

00:53:32.690 --> 00:53:33.490
research stuff.

00:53:33.490 --> 00:53:36.010
You have to go research that on
your own and then come back

00:53:36.010 --> 00:53:38.150
and say, OK, this is a real
problem that we feel very

00:53:38.150 --> 00:53:39.160
strongly about.

00:53:39.160 --> 00:53:41.940
And there are these users who
say this is an issue.

00:53:41.940 --> 00:53:44.890
And this is the scale up plan
or the development plan.

00:53:44.890 --> 00:53:46.400
VIN NARAYAN: And I can tell you
a little bit about what

00:53:46.400 --> 00:53:48.690
that conversation went with
the knee, because when it

00:53:48.690 --> 00:53:50.790
started, the student team just
had to worry mostly about the

00:53:50.790 --> 00:53:52.710
technology because there was
already a partner to scale it.

00:53:52.710 --> 00:53:55.380
But when we were deciding
whether or not we should take

00:53:55.380 --> 00:53:58.430
it forward as an independent
project and try to scale it, I

00:53:58.430 --> 00:54:00.040
think the questions really are--
and these are the same

00:54:00.040 --> 00:54:01.790
questions that D-Rev asks--

00:54:01.790 --> 00:54:04.720
can we develop it, or is there
a need for the type of things

00:54:04.720 --> 00:54:06.300
that we think we're
really good at?

00:54:06.300 --> 00:54:10.360
And are their partners available
for the other areas,

00:54:10.360 --> 00:54:12.600
is that a ripe space, are there
enough people doing the

00:54:12.600 --> 00:54:13.320
other aspects of it?

00:54:13.320 --> 00:54:16.520
So questions for us were OK, if
we make a device, are there

00:54:16.520 --> 00:54:17.670
clinics that can fit it?

00:54:17.670 --> 00:54:19.750
Are there distributors that
will be able to sell it?

00:54:19.750 --> 00:54:23.295
How much regulatory work or
other upfront costs will we

00:54:23.295 --> 00:54:24.080
need to get into it?

00:54:24.080 --> 00:54:26.710
And at the end of all that, will
it still be affordable

00:54:26.710 --> 00:54:28.950
enough for the people that
it needs to get to?

00:54:28.950 --> 00:54:31.420
And if the answers are yes, I
think that is a really ripe

00:54:31.420 --> 00:54:33.400
area for D-Rev to explore.

00:54:33.400 --> 00:54:35.180
KRISTA DONALDSON: We're really
